[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

2. The retry count is not strictly followed in some conditions.

It was discovered that even though there was a routing data change, _byteArrayZkClient was not being created anew using the newly read routing data. This would cause issues with the zookeeper endpoints provided through Helix REST. This change cleans up some internal methods and ensures that the byte array zk client gets nullified every time there is routing data change.

More specifically, the code was closing byteArrayDataAccessor but not byteArrayZkClient. This meant that the same byteArrayZkClient would be used even though everything was reset and routing data was updated. Hence, the data accessor was not really being created from scratch. Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```

[{"sha":"5a4215240076eb0647615b3ffe9048913a13e369","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Keras TB callback: Fix write_steps_per_second when profile_batch=0

cef7da10e1e944e11961f4d18978f611358023b2 introduced a bug where setting 
`write_steps_per_second` had no effect in cases where `profile_batch=0`.
This is due to an optimisation in the TensorBoard callback that disables 
calling batch hooks when not necessary.
This PR fixes it by making sure that batch level hooks are always called 
when `write_steps_per_second` is `True`.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/5a4215240076eb0647615b3ffe9048913a13e369"},{"sha":"06607a0f2c475cc9602f2c5d190b6b6e41b8ef33","author":{"name":"Dave Moore","email":"d1e2c048df802fa00ca98fd8ad6a2d561f813eb7@google.com"},"message":"Support numpy scalar types in serialized TypeSpecs.

Currently, code of the form

```
v = tf.get_static_value(some_int_tensor)
# type(v) == np.int32
hash(SomeTypeSpec(some_arg=v))
```

breaks because the checks for Python scalar types don't recognize Numpy scalars.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

parameters to the test scripts:

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]

...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. [{"sha":"4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Raising the memory allocation cap for GPU unit tests from 1GB to 2GB

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

This allows the `test_with_renode.sh` script to be called via the
makefile with all the parameters needed to run on a given target, while
also staying consistent with the other test scripts.

As a result of this change, the makefile is passing in the following
parameters to the test scripts:
 #1 - test binary path
 #2 - string to determine that test passes
 #3 - target

Parameter #3 is only used for `test_with_renode.sh`

Manually tested that the following commands now pass:
```

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

This PR adds the necessary updates to make it run correctly on ROCm.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/89ef24d67ad20048d9afbdea8587bc2bc325fa41"},{"sha":"5a4215240076eb0647615b3ffe9048913a13e369","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Keras TB callback: Fix write_steps_per_second when profile_batch=0

cef7da10e1e944e11961f4d18978f611358023b2 introduced a bug where setting 
`write_steps_per_second` had no effect in cases where `profile_batch=0`.
This is due to an optimisation in the TensorBoard callback that disables

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]

...
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. * https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

[{"sha":"e42a2b8dc9e172023759914304d5f451c7dc3950","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for breakage in XLA Conv Op functionality

The following commit breaks Conv Op functionality (in the XLA backend) for ROCm platform.

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50

The cause seems to be that the `scratch_size` field in the new `GpuConvDescriptor` is not getting correctly populated in the new MLIR path. It is being used correctly in the convolution runner code.

declaration:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-6453912dbc4ee715a56da9d7b218b52795dea2aa631a482101fc6d58c573d9ccR122-R135

use (get access) in conv runner:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-a01181d08b28a9c7432f22439622f16725126184283a73822c70b2151098a8adR277

set access in non-MLIR(?) based path:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-a01181d08b28a9c7432f22439622f16725126184283a73822c70b2151098a8adR450

This commit merely adds the missing "set" in the MLIR based path","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/e42a2b8dc9e172023759914304d5f451c7dc3950"},{"sha":"4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Raising the memory allocation cap for GPU unit tests from 1GB to 2GB

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"89dd5837aa3a0a5d5ccd39f7c963b668eebbaab4","author":{"name":"A. Problem: 
- current setup requires 2 different containers (elixir and node:12)
- any change in JS files invalidates the cache and requires `npm install`

Solution:
- install Node 12 + NPM directly on the Elixir alpine image + use “sticky” versions, as described here: https://superuser.com/questions/1055060/how-to-install-a-specific-package-version-in-alpine
- unify `npm-setup` + `npm` steps
- copy package.json + lockfile separatelly and run `npm install` prior to running JS tests to benefit from better caching","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mindreframer/phoenix/commits/d7c89a2f48295c9428755b356785d9731725726f"}]

[{"sha":"4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Raising the memory allocation cap for GPU unit tests from 1GB to 2GB

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"89dd5837aa3a0a5d5ccd39f7c963b668eebbaab4","author":{"name":"A. This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]

...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

[{"sha":"523f789ecdd129b1edc3525b9f36e9d4a1c278ec","author":{"name":"Ryan Kuester","email":"bb3a6f28aedef659ba69a612b2c1e9f77b8f692b@bdti.com"},"message":"micro: delete gmock/gtest includes in copy of SPACE_TO_DEPTH

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op SPACE_TO_DEPTH. There is an annoying difference
between internal and external versions of the code that causes
clang-formatting errors in CI checks. When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rkuester/tensorflow/commits/523f789ecdd129b1edc3525b9f36e9d4a1c278ec"}]

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"14246bd0280d1c5e5564eedd4927bf9af9339967","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46221 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_rocm_raise_cap_2GB

breaks because the checks for Python scalar types don't recognize Numpy scalars.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

The following commit breaks Conv Op functionality (in the XLA backend) for ROCm platform.

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50

The cause seems to be that the `scratch_size` field in the new `GpuConvDescriptor` is not getting correctly populated in the new MLIR path. It is being used correctly in the convolution runner code.

declaration:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-6453912dbc4ee715a56da9d7b218b52795dea2aa631a482101fc6d58c573d9ccR122-R135

use (get access) in conv runner:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-a01181d08b28a9c7432f22439622f16725126184283a73822c70b2151098a8adR277

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```

...

```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```

```

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"89dd5837aa3a0a5d5ccd39f7c963b668eebbaab4","author":{"name":"A. [{"sha":"c30b352174f2c2346bb66ef7d977abc7299ef117","author":{"name":"Ryan Kuester","email":"bb3a6f28aedef659ba69a612b2c1e9f77b8f692b@bdti.com"},"message":"micro: delete gmock/gtest includes in copy of DEPTH_TO_SPACE

Delete the gmock and gtest includes in the currently inactive
copy of op DEPTH_TO_SPACE. There is an annoying difference
between internal and external versions of the code that causes
clang-formatting errors in CI checks. When the code is imported
internally, the gmock and gtest includes become:

    #include "/internal/path/to/gmock/gmock.h"

and then clang-format wants them to be in the lower include block
(i.e., next to "flatbuffers/flatbuffers.h").

The solution for now is to delete gmock and gtest includes when
making these operator copies.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rkuester/tensorflow/commits/c30b352174f2c2346bb66ef7d977abc7299ef117"}]

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"487b5ff519ad99ae1e0b7e50105c7bdd81077721","author":{"name":"Võ Văn Nghĩa","email":"75014dab1593e9d2357d6ece2ffccc60a564f757@gmail.com"},"message":"add `CheckTensorValue`","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/487b5ff519ad99ae1e0b7e50105c7bdd81077721"},{"sha":"5c1bc1cc4087062a051a9e9a84a9e10a29b33fb8","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46183 from ek9852:nnapi_trans_conv_quant_fix

[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]

...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. cef7da10e1e944e11961f4d18978f611358023b2 introduced a bug where setting 
`write_steps_per_second` had no effect in cases where `profile_batch=0`.
This is due to an optimisation in the TensorBoard callback that disables

[{"sha":"4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Raising the memory allocation cap for GPU unit tests from 1GB to 2GB

This PR/commit updates the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` script to raise the GPU memory allocation cap from 1GB to 2GB when running unit-tests.

Recently a couple of unit tests started failing on the ROCm platform because they were running out of memory

```
//tensorflow/python/kernel_tests:extract_image_patches_grad_test_gpu
//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu
```

GPU unit tests (atleast on the ROCm platform) are run with a cap that is set and implemented as shown here :

* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/gpu_build/parallel_gpu_execute.sh#L26-L32
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L130-L137
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L151
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L487-L503

It does not seem that the `parallel_gpu_execute.sh` is being used on the CUDA platform (anymore...think it was in the past). There does not seem to be any reference to it in the `Invocation Details` tab of the `Linux GPU` CI job.

for e.g - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/details

It also does not seem that GPU unit tests on the CUDA platform are being subjected to the 1GB memory cap. This can be verified by looking the at `Target Log` for the `//tensorflow/python/ops/numpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu` test in the `Linux GPU` CI job (actually any GPU unit test)

for e.g. - https://source.cloud.google.com/results/invocations/09d63e6a-f7a9-4fc6-9708-2fdd40b8b193/targets/%2F%2Ftensorflow%2Fpython%2Fops%2Fnumpy_ops:np_interop_test_gpu/log

On the ROCm platform, we see the following log messages which are generated as a consequence of the memory cap (when TF tried to grab the entire available GPU memory on startup)

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc#L488-L494

```
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 16133306368 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 14519974912 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 13067976704 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
 W tensorflow/stream_executor/stream_executor_pimpl.cc:490] Not enough memory to allocate 11761178624 on device 0 within provided limit. [used=0, limit=1073741824]
...
...
...
```

These messsage are not present in unit tests logs for `Linux GPU` CI job, which seems to suggest that the env var `TF_PER_DEVICE_MEMORY_LIMIT_MB` is not set when the unit tests are run. Either that or the GPU on which the tests are being run has 1GB total memory which is unlikely.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/4574fb2176c920e5f30e2c4f3d54482fb0a9cc45"},{"sha":"14246bd0280d1c5e5564eedd4927bf9af9339967","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46221 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_rocm_raise_cap_2GB

[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

[{"sha":"0c244ad5214e28aed150bd28433fea37df8b479a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"PSv2: Shutdown the worker preemption thread in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.

When ClusterCoordinator's destructor is called, mark the worker preemption thread as finished to stop the thread.

Notices the Cluster and Worker objects will not be destroyed due to the threading.Thread object holds a reference to the cluster object.

There will be 2 following CLs to address the Cluster/Worker deletion:
1. Close the worker threads in ClusterCoordinator's destructor.
2. Use weakref as target function for threading.Thread objects, to ensure Cluster/Worker objects can be garbage collected in memory.

The following commit breaks Conv Op functionality (in the XLA backend) for ROCm platform.

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50

The cause seems to be that the `scratch_size` field in the new `GpuConvDescriptor` is not getting correctly populated in the new MLIR path. It is being used correctly in the convolution runner code.

declaration:

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/8684c6b2e95601542c6c5c006bde5dd50f589a50#diff-6453912dbc4ee715a56da9d7b218b52795dea2aa631a482101fc6d58c573d9ccR122-R135

use (get access) in conv runner:
